c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

void removeOuterParentheses(char *s, char *result) {
    int count = 0;
    int resIndex = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(s); i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resIndex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else { // s[i] == ')'
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resIndex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resIndex] = '\0';  // Null terminate the result string
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "(()())(())(()(()))";
    char result[100];  // Make sure this buffer is large enough
    removeOuterParentheses(s, result);
    printf("%s\n", result);
    return 0;
}

Short answer:
No, C does not have a native string datatype like Java or Python.

Long answer (with some drama ):

In C, strings are actually just arrays of characters (char[]), ending with a special null character '\0' to mark the end of the string.

For example:

c
char str[] = "Hello";

Under the hood, its stored like:

| 'H' | 'e' | 'l' | 'l' | 'o' | '\0' |

So in C:

  • You deal with character arrays.

  • No fancy StringBuilder or .length(). Instead you have strlen() (from <string.h>).

  • Modifying strings means modifying arrays directly.

  • And you must always remember the '\0' or you risk weird bugs .

ChatGPT said:

BOOM!
Great question, detective! You just stepped on one of the most common C mistakes

Main Problem:

You're returning result which is a local array inside the function.

In C:

  • Local arrays (like char result[100]) are stored in the stack.

  • Once the function returns, the stack frame is destroyed result becomes garbage memory.

  • So when you return result, you're returning a pointer to something that no longer exists.

Undefined behavior (aka surprise bugs party ).

Other issue:

Inside your loop:

c
if (count > 0) { result[resultindex++] = s[i]; }

  • For '(' you increment count before checking count > 0.

  • So you're actually always adding '(', even for outermost opening.

  • The logic should be:

c
if (s[i] == '(') {
    if (count > 0) { result[resultindex++] = s[i]; }
    count++;
}

(Notice: check before increment for '(', check after decrement for ')')

Solution Options:

Option 1 Use dynamic allocation (safe return)

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

char* removeOuterParentheses(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char* result = (char*)malloc(len + 1);  // allocate memory dynamically
    int resultindex = 0;
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else {
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resultindex] = '\0';
    return result;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "(()())(())";
    char* output = removeOuterParentheses(s);
    printf("%s\n", output);
    free(output);  // free allocated memory
    return 0;
}

Option 2 If you really want to use fixed-size, pass result array from caller:

c
void removeOuterParentheses(char* s, char* result) {
    int resultindex = 0;
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(s); i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else {
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resultindex] = '\0';
}

Then call like this:

c
char s[] = "(()())(())";
char result[100];
removeOuterParentheses(s, result);
printf("%s\n", result);

The moral of C:

If you're returning a string, always be careful where the memory lives. Heap (malloc) is safe; stack is dangerous.

Why len - i - 1 ?

Because:

  • len gives total length.

  • i moves from start (0) to end (len - 1).

  • But we want to copy from end to start.

  • So:

"Wherever i is, take the mirror position from the end: len - i - 1."

Mirror index formula!

When to use len - i - 1?

Anytime you're reversing an array or string!
Whenever you want to map:
first index last index,
second index second last,
third index third last...

Funny way to remember:

"When you're reversing, think of a mirror. The leftmost dude becomes the rightmost dude. So for index i, his mirror twin is len - i - 1."

FULL CODE

Heres your C code, with love and friendship :

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <ctype.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Utility to reverse part of string from left to right indexes
void reverse(char *s, int left, int right) {
    while (left < right) {
        char temp = s[left];
        s[left] = s[right];
        s[right] = temp;
        left++;
        right--;
    }
}

char* reverseWords(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char *result = (char*)malloc(len + 1);
    strcpy(result, s);  // Make a copy of original string

    // Step 1: Reverse whole string
    reverse(result, 0, len - 1);

    // Step 2: Reverse each word
    int start = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
        if (result[i] == ' ' || result[i] == '\0') {
            reverse(result, start, i - 1);
            start = i + 1;
        }
    }

    return result;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "hello world I am Asma";
    char* output = reverseWords(s);
    printf("%s\n", output);
    free(output);
    return 0;
}

Explanation:

  • reverse() function reverses characters between given indices.

  • First, reverse whole string.

  • Then reverse each word one-by-one by finding spaces.

The problem you're facing:

WHAT YOU NEED TO DO

1 First: Trim the input string (remove leading & trailing spaces)

C doesn't have built-in trim() like Python or Java... so we build it ourselves

FULL SOLUTION:

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <ctype.h>

// Utility to reverse part of string from left to right indexes
void reverse(char *s, int left, int right) {
    while (left < right) {
        char temp = s[left];
        s[left] = s[right];
        s[right] = temp;
        left++;
        right--;
    }
}

// Function to trim and reduce spaces
char* cleanSpaces(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char* cleaned = (char*)malloc(len + 1);
    int i = 0, j = 0;
    
    // Skip leading spaces
    while (s[i] == ' ') i++;
    
    while (s[i] != '\0') {
        if (s[i] != ' ') {
            cleaned[j++] = s[i++];
        } else {
            // add one space
            cleaned[j++] = ' ';
            i++;
            // skip multiple spaces
            while (s[i] == ' ') i++;
        }
    }

    // Remove trailing space if exists
    if (j > 0 && cleaned[j - 1] == ' ') j--;
    cleaned[j] = '\0';
    return cleaned;
}

char* reverseWords(char* s) {
    char* cleaned = cleanSpaces(s);
    int len = strlen(cleaned);

    // Reverse full string
    reverse(cleaned, 0, len - 1);

    // Reverse each word
    int start = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
        if (cleaned[i] == ' ' || cleaned[i] == '\0') {
            reverse(cleaned, start, i - 1);
            start = i + 1;
        }
    }

    return cleaned;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "  hello world  ";
    char* output = reverseWords(s);
    printf("\"%s\"\n", output);
    free(output);
    return 0;
}

The trickiest part is cleanSpaces() function:

Skips leading spaces
Reduces multiple spaces to single
Removes trailing space

You can write your own trim() like this:

c
char* trim(char* s) {
    int start = 0;
    int end = strlen(s) - 1;

    while (s[start] == ' ') start++;
    while (end >= start && s[end] == ' ') end--;

    int newLen = end - start + 1;
    char* trimmed = (char*)malloc(newLen + 1);
    strncpy(trimmed, s + start, newLen);
    trimmed[newLen] = '\0';

    return trimmed;
}
